    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-01T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-01T13:00:00-05:00" n="181"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./168: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-01T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 1, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 1—2:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>87. Department’s circular January 31, 7 p.m. Marchandeau, Minister of Commerce,
                    lunched at the Embassy today and I discussed with him the breakdown of
                    commercial negotiations with the Soviet Government reading to him the text of
                    the statement given out in Washington.</p>
                <p>He said that the American offer appeared to him more favorable than anything the
                    French were prepared to offer at this time particularly with respect to a
                    revolving fund for credit and that he was sure that the negotiations had broken
                    down on the question of any recognition of debts no matter what their origin. He
                    said that the Soviet authorities had naturally endeavored to play France off
                    against the American group and vice versa in the matter of these negotiations
                    and that he was very pleased to have the definite information of our positive
                    attitude.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Straus</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
